00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:24.876
&gt;&gt; Playing dead by Andrew Hudgins.

00:06:26.510 --> 00:06:26.643
Our father liked to play a game.

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:30.310
He played that he was dead.

00:06:30.510 --> 00:06:30.966
He took his thick black glasses
off and stretched out on the bed.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:34.690
He wouldn't twitch and didn't
snore or move in any way.

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:39.616
He didn't even seem to breathe!

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:41.973
We asked, Are you okay?

00:06:43.770 --> 00:06:47.636
We tickled fingers up and down
his huge, pink, stinky feet.

00:06:49.280 --> 00:06:52.946
He didn't move; he lay as
still as last year's parakeet.

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:57.946
We pushed our fingers up his
nose, and wiggled them inside.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:07:00.650
Next, we peeled his eyelids back.

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:02.590
Are you okay?

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:08.323
We cried. I really thought he might
be dead and not just playing possum,

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:14.326
because his eyeballs didn't twitch
when I slid my tongue across 'em.

00:07:17.710 --> 00:07:21.910
He's dead, we sobbed-but to be
sure, I jabbed him in the jewels.

00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:29.050
He rose, like Jesus, from the dead,
though I don't think Jesus drools.

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:33.973
His right hand lashed
both right and left.

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:34.613
His left hand clutched his scrotum.

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:41.193
And the words he yelled-I know damn
well I'm way too young to quote 'em.

