I mean obviously Amber was like
awesome but I remember Will,

00:18:10.180 --> 00:18:13.913
Will left a really strong
impression on me because he was

00:18:14.140 --> 00:18:16.006
so ridiculously un dramatic.

00:18:16.700 --> 00:18:20.833
He was so honest and like, almost
dead pan in a sense but like,

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:22.210
he was just, I don't know he was
just so straight forward about it,

00:18:24.990 --> 00:18:25.893
and I think that's what Amber
was able to convey as well.

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:28.566
I think that's what the
judges try to look for,

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:30.350
it's just that honesty
instead of that you know sort

00:18:33.330 --> 00:18:33.983
of an exaggerated tone that
you might see sometimes

00:18:36.010 --> 00:18:36.273
at like some poetry readings but
I'm, yeah, I am trying to make it

00:18:40.080 --> 00:18:40.313
as honest as possible it's
really important, and yeah,

00:18:43.380 --> 00:18:48.180
I think we all try to do the best we
can but yeah, just trying to be true

00:18:48.620 --> 00:18:52.486
to yourself and sure to the
poem and that's all you can do.

00:18:52.510 --> 00:18:53.510
[ Applause ]

00:19:00.180 --> 00:19:02.180
&gt;&gt; And that's not easy to do--

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:02.980
what they do, all three
of them here today.

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:07.046
Next I want to introduce
Amber Rose Johnson.

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:10.276
Last April, Amber Rose Johnson,
a junior at Classical high school

00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:14.090
in Providence Rhode Island won
the title of National Champion

00:19:16.490 --> 00:19:19.356
of the 2010 Poetry Out
Loud national finals.

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:19.923
She advanced from a
very competitive field

00:19:22.010 --> 00:19:24.076
to claim a 20,000 dollar price.

00:19:24.610 --> 00:19:29.143
As the POL national champion, Amber
has been a guess on MPRs the best

00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:33.123
of our knowledge, alongside
Natalie Merchant, Bobby McFerrin

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:35.216
and Rae Armantrout, and others.

00:19:35.530 --> 00:19:35.933
Amber also participated
in the poetry--

00:19:37.660 --> 00:19:38.756
the panel on poetry at the American
Library Association Conference held

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:41.640
in D.C. this summer and will
perform along Rhode Island poets

00:19:44.820 --> 00:19:49.086
at The Library of Congress', Poetry
at Noon Series on October 19.

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:50.186
Her favorite poets are Maya Angelou
and Nikki Giovanni and she hopes

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:57.640
to pursue a career in public
policy and political science.

00:19:58.010 --> 00:19:59.010
Welcome Amber.

00:20:00.510 --> 00:20:01.510
[ Applause ]

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:09.426
&gt;&gt; Hello, hello.

00:20:10.390 --> 00:20:12.790
Oh, my dad is right
there [laughter].

00:20:13.210 --> 00:20:13.236
I was looking for him
but he is right there.

00:20:16.050 --> 00:20:20.450
Aren't they amazing [applause] Umm,
so, I'm gonna do the last piece

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:24.946
that I did at the national
competitions this year.

00:20:27.820 --> 00:20:30.686
It's called For My
People by Margaret Walker

00:20:31.510 --> 00:20:32.510
[ Pause ]

00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:42.576
&gt;&gt; For my people everywhere singing
their slave songs repeatedly,

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:50.920


00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:55.213
their dirges and their ditties
and their blues and jubilees,

00:20:58.930 --> 00:21:02.063
praying their prayers
nightly to an unknown god,

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:08.470
bending their knees
humbly to an unseen power;

00:21:12.770 --> 00:21:13.770


00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:18.366
For my people lending their strength
to the years, to the gone years

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:24.946
and the now years and the maybe
years, washing, ironing, cooking,

00:21:31.050 --> 00:21:35.383
scrubbing, sewing, mending hoeing
plowing digging planting pruning

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:40.686
patching dragging along never
gaining never reaping never knowing

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:48.546
and never understanding; For my
playmates in the clay and dust

00:21:57.700 --> 00:22:01.700
and sand of Alabama backyards
playing baptizing and preaching

00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:09.623
and doctor and jail and soldier
and school and mama and cooking

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:14.960
and playhouse and concert and
store and hair and Miss Choomby

00:22:15.620 --> 00:22:19.753
and company; For the cramped
bewildered years we went to school

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:27.880
to learn to know the reasons why and
the answers to and the people who

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:34.693
and the places where and the days
when, in memory of the bitter hours

00:22:40.970 --> 00:22:45.236
when we discovered we were black
and poor and small and different

00:22:54.460 --> 00:22:58.326
and nobody cared and nobody
wondered and nobody understood.

00:23:08.200 --> 00:23:09.200


00:23:10.990 --> 00:23:15.256
For the boys and girls who grew
in spite of these thing to be man

00:23:20.110 --> 00:23:24.576
and woman, to laugh and dance and
sing and play and drink their wine

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:33.096
and religion and success, to marry
their playmates and bear children

00:23:37.230 --> 00:23:40.630
and then die of consumption
and anemia and lynching.

00:23:53.380 --> 00:23:56.246
For my people walking
blindly spreading joy,

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:02.060


00:24:02.120 --> 00:24:06.653
losing time being lazy, sleeping
when hungry, shouting when burdened,

00:24:09.810 --> 00:24:14.343
drinking when hopeless, tied and
shackled and tangled among ourselves

00:24:19.650 --> 00:24:23.916
by the unseen creatures who tower
over us omnisciently and laugh;

00:24:27.340 --> 00:24:31.473
For my people thronging 47th
Street in Chicago and Lenox Avenue

00:24:37.650 --> 00:24:40.650
in New York and Rampart
Street in New Orleans,

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:49.026
lost disinherited dispossessed and
happy people filling the cabarets

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:56.413
and taverns and other people's
pockets and looking for bread

00:24:56.570 --> 00:25:00.036
and shoes and milk and land
and money and something--

00:25:03.110 --> 00:25:07.510
something all our own; For my people
walking blundering and groping

00:25:11.170 --> 00:25:11.410
and floundering in the dark of
churches and schools and clubs

00:25:14.930 --> 00:25:15.100
and societies, associations
and councils and committees

00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:22.760
and conventions, distressed and
disturbed and deceived and devoured

00:25:26.450 --> 00:25:30.716
by money-hungry, glory-craving
leeches, preyed on by facile force

00:25:34.500 --> 00:25:38.766
of state and fad and novelty, by
false prophet and holy believer;

00:25:39.750 --> 00:25:43.750
For my people standing staring
trying to fashion a better way

00:25:45.190 --> 00:25:48.590
from confusion, from
hypocrisy and misunderstanding,

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:54.666
trying to fashion a world that will
hold all the people, all the faces,

00:26:03.430 --> 00:26:04.430


00:26:04.570 --> 00:26:08.170
all the Adams and Eves and
their countless generations.

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:11.740


00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:14.910
Let a new earth rise.

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:22.283
Let another world be born.

00:26:23.550 --> 00:26:26.216
Let a bloody peace by
written in the sky.

00:26:26.430 --> 00:26:29.830
Let a second generation
fill of courage issue forth;

00:26:30.830 --> 00:26:33.630
let a people loving
freedom come to growth.

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:37.973
Let a beauty full of healing
and strength of final clenching

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:44.166
by the pulsing in our
spirits and our blood.

00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:48.326
Let the martial songs by
written, let the dirges disappear.

00:26:52.040 --> 00:26:53.040


00:26:55.170 --> 00:26:58.036
Let a race of men now
rise and take control.

00:27:07.510 --> 00:27:08.510
[ Applause ]

00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:23.220
&gt;&gt; Thank you Amber, I wanted
to ask you a question too.

00:27:26.790 --> 00:27:31.456
Beside the cash prize, you are about
half way to your 10 year as Poetry

00:27:32.250 --> 00:27:34.050
Out loud national champion.

00:27:34.250 --> 00:27:35.250
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:27:36.250 --> 00:27:37.183
&gt;&gt; And in my introduction,
I read up a series

00:27:38.250 --> 00:27:39.810
of public appearances you've been
making and even talking about poetry

00:27:41.290 --> 00:27:43.023
as well as about your life

00:27:43.290 --> 00:27:44.570
and I know you have a political
career paths ahead of you.

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:50.143
I want you to talk a little about
what it has meant to be a Poetry

00:27:50.530 --> 00:27:53.996
Out Loud national champion
to you and you know what--

00:27:54.270 --> 00:27:54.843
is there any difference before
you won the title and now,

00:27:57.430 --> 00:27:58.500
and what you've learned and
what this has meant to you?

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:02.093
&gt;&gt; Wow, that's quite a question.

00:28:03.980 --> 00:28:08.113
Umm, becoming national champion
has absolutely changed my life.

00:28:12.060 --> 00:28:13.793
My entire life, woop done.

00:28:14.420 --> 00:28:14.780
Old Amber is completely
gone, completely changed.

00:28:17.260 --> 00:28:20.926
It's definitely a big change
from being a state champion

00:28:21.410 --> 00:28:26.010
to national champion and I remember
I competed two years ago, as well.

00:28:27.390 --> 00:28:28.066
When Shawntay Henry was the national
champion and I remember looking

00:28:31.180 --> 00:28:31.530
at her and looking at Will
Farley and being like,

00:28:34.030 --> 00:28:38.363
men they are so cool like, I wanna
be them and now that I'm in it,

00:28:40.220 --> 00:28:40.400
it's just-- it's absolutely
amazing, the way, I--

00:28:43.240 --> 00:28:46.106
the way I used to see
the national champion,

00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:47.596
I know that people are looking
at me that way and just knowing

00:28:49.290 --> 00:28:50.423
that other students are
getting the same feeling

00:28:51.290 --> 00:28:52.070
but you also have a certain level of
responsibility as national champion,

00:28:55.310 --> 00:28:56.043
definitely wherever I go, I don't
just wanna talk about myself.

00:28:58.710 --> 00:28:59.543
I wanna talk about all the
amazing state champions.

00:29:01.210 --> 00:29:01.440
I wanna talk about the entire
experience and how Poetry

00:29:04.580 --> 00:29:07.846
Out Loud is still growing,
I don't-- it's, insane.

00:29:10.510 --> 00:29:11.520
I feel like every morning I wake
up and sometimes I'm like whoa,

00:29:13.700 --> 00:29:14.770
I'm a national champion, like
its never really hits you

00:29:16.230 --> 00:29:17.963
and never really sinks it.

00:29:18.230 --> 00:29:19.683
I think I finally understand it
when I'm at the nationals in April

00:29:21.110 --> 00:29:22.043
and heading off the title maybe
that's when it hit me but as

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:25.650
of right now, I'm kinda still
in the whirlwind [applause].

00:29:26.370 --> 00:29:27.370
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:32.386
We have some time to
have one more question.

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:33.846
I also wanted to ask you
the methodology question,

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:35.626
you know, how do you choose poems?

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:37.426
Are you still memorizing poems?

00:29:39.360 --> 00:29:40.360
And you know?

00:29:41.360 --> 00:29:43.640
For all the poetry lovers in the
audience, what does it mean to you

00:29:43.480 --> 00:29:44.623
to internalize a poem and how do
you memorize and how do you go

00:29:46.470 --> 00:29:48.203
about your work with that?

00:29:49.260 --> 00:29:51.660
&gt;&gt; Umm, in terms of
choosing my poem,

00:29:51.710 --> 00:29:54.510
it was always a really
a family experience.

00:29:54.700 --> 00:29:55.100
I have great family support at home.

00:29:56.700 --> 00:29:57.783
My dad is here with me today and
it was always the whole family

00:29:59.750 --> 00:30:00.440
that kind of chose the poem because,
wherever I go I wanna speak life,

00:30:03.660 --> 00:30:05.726
I wanna carry a positive image.

00:30:05.770 --> 00:30:09.570
So, I'm kind of didn't want
any poems that were overly sad

00:30:10.020 --> 00:30:10.380
or depressing or anything like that.

00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:12.120
I wanted a poem that reflected me
and reflected something positive.

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:19.200
And in terms of memorizing,
like Will said,

00:30:19.810 --> 00:30:20.210
that's definitely a gradual process.

00:30:21.810 --> 00:30:22.610
It's not something that
happens over night.

00:30:23.810 --> 00:30:24.380
It's just about, you now,
taking it one step at a time,

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:28.840
trying not to get overwhelmed.

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:29.516
If you do motions, if ever
you're trying to memorize poems,

00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:32.763
do motions, that helps it
does, like if you are trying

00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:39.830
to remember something and you do
a motion it will definitely click.

00:30:40.660 --> 00:30:40.820
But I mean, I had a
coach for this year,

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:43.963
last year when I competed
I didn't have coach

00:30:45.170 --> 00:30:45.836
and that definitely
helped but it's just,

00:30:47.170 --> 00:30:47.940
it's trying to find the
heartbeat of the poem.

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:50.823
Because, when you do Poetry Out Loud
I think what Will was trying to get

00:30:52.710 --> 00:30:53.186
at between-- the different routine
a recitation and a performance

00:30:56.500 --> 00:31:01.233
or over dramatize, drama-- yeah that
word is when you find the heartbeat

00:31:04.520 --> 00:31:05.396
of the poem, because I wanna
take Amber out of the poem.

00:31:07.310 --> 00:31:08.310
I'm sure they wanna take Will
and Youssef out of the poem.

00:31:10.110 --> 00:31:10.843
That's not what the
performances is about;

00:31:12.110 --> 00:31:13.043
it's about finding the
heartbeat of the poem.

00:31:14.110 --> 00:31:15.576
Finding the heartbeat of the
author that wrote the poem,

00:31:16.310 --> 00:31:17.333
really understanding and letting
the word speaks for themselves

00:31:19.420 --> 00:31:20.153
and that's really when
you master the poem

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:22.553
when you can't let the
word speak for themselves

00:31:23.420 --> 00:31:24.820
and take yourself completely
out of it so [applause]

00:31:25.420 --> 00:31:27.953
&gt;&gt; We have time for
one more quick one,

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:32.136
and has this helped you
in your writing at all?

00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:36.190
And do you write poetry?

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:39.856
Or is this just a separate
art for you completely.

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:44.240
&gt;&gt; Poetry Out Loud kind of has
touched every area of my life,

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:45.386
it definitely helps
when it comes, you know,

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:50.720
when your English teach tells you
you're doing a poetry segment,

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:51.810
I'm like yes.

00:31:52.810 --> 00:31:53.150
My favorite segment, but it
definitely has changed my writing

00:31:56.470 --> 00:31:58.403
and the way I looked at words

00:31:58.470 --> 00:31:58.963
because I understand how
powerful words can really be now

00:32:01.710 --> 00:32:02.733
and I understand that the way
you structure something on a page

00:32:04.820 --> 00:32:04.846
or the way you put two words
together can really take

00:32:08.260 --> 00:32:08.933
like completely change
the impact of the poem

00:32:10.520 --> 00:32:12.386
and the meaning of the poem.

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:14.496
So, I definitely take that into
consideration, but I have also found

00:32:15.010 --> 00:32:15.856
that now whenever I look at a poem
or whenever I hear a poem I think

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:19.003
about so much more
than just listening.

00:32:20.790 --> 00:32:22.753
I think about what the author
was going through when they wrote

00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:24.650
that poem, I think about what
that poem was supposed to mean,

00:32:25.270 --> 00:32:26.070
I think about the time
that it was written.

00:32:27.270 --> 00:32:27.913
I think about the person
who's reciting it

00:32:29.360 --> 00:32:30.613
and when you do a competition
like that, you really start

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:32.813
to breakdown a poem and it means it
is much more than just, you know,

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:37.400
something written on the page.

00:32:37.400 --> 00:32:38.400
[applause]

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:40.400
&gt;&gt; Good answer.

00:32:41.400 --> 00:32:43.000
That's very interesting.

00:32:43.400 --> 00:32:44.760
As an organizer for Poetry Out
Loud, it such a privilege to be able

00:32:46.440 --> 00:32:46.690
to get inside the minds of these
kids, that are so good at this.

00:32:50.390 --> 00:32:54.590
I want to remind all high school
teachers here that we have kits

00:32:55.210 --> 00:32:55.720
in the back for Poetry
Out Loud to start

00:32:57.300 --> 00:32:58.493
that new classroom please
visit the tables in the back

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:01.573
and thank you fro being here.

00:33:02.140 --> 00:33:03.140
[ Pause ]

